.TH GORM 1 "December 21, 2025" "Gorm 1.5.0" "GNUstep User Commands"
.SH NAME
gorm \- GNUstep interface builder
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B openapp Gorm
.RI [ file.gorm ]
.br
.B Gorm
.RI [ file.gorm ]
.br
.B gormtool
.RI [ options ] " inputfile"
.SH DESCRIPTION
Gorm (GNUstep Object Relationship Modeler) is a graphical interface builder for GNUstep. It lets you compose windows, menus, controllers, and other interface objects, connect outlets and actions, and save the resulting interface archive as .gorm, .xib or .nib style resources. Gorm mirrors the functionality of the NeXTSTEP/OpenStep/Cocoa Interface Builder while targeting the GNUstep frameworks.
.PP
Launch Gorm without arguments to start a new untitled interface document. Passing a .gorm file opens an existing document. The application participates in the standard GNUstep document architecture, so files passed on the command line or via the workspace are opened in-place.
.SH OPTIONS
Gorm is typically started without special options; any argument ending in .gorm (or another supported interface extension) is opened as a document. Standard GNUstep GUI options (such as backend selection) are also honored.
.SS gormtool options
The accompanying gormtool command provides headless import/export tasks for interface archives. Its primary options are:
.TP
.B --read \fIpath\fR
Open the specified interface archive. If omitted, the last argument is treated as the input file.
.TP
.B --write \fIpath\fR
Write the processed archive to the given path instead of replacing the input.
.TP
.B --import-strings-file \fIpath\fR
Import a Cocoa/GNUstep .strings file and replace matching text in the interface archive.
.TP
.B --export-strings-file \fIpath\fR
Export all user-visible strings from the interface archive to the specified .strings file.
.TP
.B --export-xliff \fIpath\fR
Export an XLIFF 1.2 translation file from the interface archive.
.TP
.B --import-xliff \fIpath\fR
Import translations from an XLIFF 1.2 file into the interface archive.
.TP
.B --import-class \fIheader\fR
Parse the Objective-C header, adding the class to the archive; existing instances may have their connections broken when re-imported.
.TP
.B --export-class \fIname\fR
Export the named class from the archive to a header in the current directory.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I *.gorm
Primary interface documents produced by Gorm.
.TP
.I *.nib
Legacy Interface Builder archives that can be opened and saved by Gorm.
.TP
.I *.xib
Modern Interface Builder archives that can be opened and saved by Gorm.
.TP
.I ~/.GNUstepDefaults
NSUserDefaults database where Gorm preferences are stored on GNUstep systems.
.SH EXAMPLES
Start a new document:
.PP
.RS
.B openapp Gorm
.RE
.PP
Open an existing archive from the shell:
.PP
.RS
.B Gorm MyWindow.gorm
.RE
.PP
Export localizable strings from an interface archive:
.PP
.RS
.B gormtool --export-strings-file MyWindow.strings MyWindow.gorm
.RE
.PP
Round-trip translations with XLIFF:
.PP
.RS
.B gormtool --export-xliff MyWindow.xliff MyWindow.gorm
.br
.B gormtool --import-xliff MyWindow.xliff MyWindow.gorm
.RE
